In article <1992Mar09.091133.11209@cs.ruu.nl> 
	nevries@cs.ruu.nl (Nico de Vries) writes:

>I read multiple times of people comparing house locks with software
>locks. The claim goes like 'would you give an universal house lock
>cracker to anyone ?'. This comparision is WRONG. If SOME house lock
>can be opened in a few seconds the house owner needs to know this too.

	False, if in the analogy they had the craker then one could right ?.

>Furthermore replacing a software lock is much easier than replacing
>a group of house locks.

	Perhaps, but most people don't have source - they have to take
the time to buy something if replacement is not at zero cost, etc.

>The widely used placebo security in PKZIP is a real problem. 

	It depends on how many can break it at any time. A door lock
is a good example because people in the know can break them as can
programmers in the know for the other case.	

